      "text": "[…] It is a \n\"perspective   by incongruity,\" since it is established by violating the\n \"proprieties\" of the word in its previous   linkages. […] Nietzsche establishes his perspectives by a   constant juxtaposing of \nincongruous words, „attaching to some name a qualifying epithet which had\n   heretofore gone with a different order of names.   He writes by the \nsame constant reordering of categories that we find in the Shakespearean\n metaphor."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8374689e9f9dddbf",
      "text": "Indeed, the metaphor always has about it precisely this revealing of hitherto unsuspected connectives which we may note in the progressions of a [[Dream]]. It appeals by exemplifying relationships between objects which our customary rational vocabulary has ignored. Were we finally to accommodate ourselves, for instance, to placing the lion in the cat family, a poet might metaphorically enlighten us and startle us by speaking of \"that big dog, the lion\"—or were we completely inured to thinking of man as an ape, we might get a sudden flash, or perspective, from a reference to man as the \"ape-God\"."
    },
